Major Serhiy Volyna of the 36th separate marine brigade in the besieged port city Mariupol told the Washington Post that his soldiers "will not lay down our weapons" and would continue "to conduct combat operations and to complete our military tasks as long as we receive them". The fearless message comes hours after Putin asked for a ceasefire in the southeastern city. Meanwhile, as Russian military losses mount, Kremlin insiders are reportedly questioning the decision to launch the attack. Some members of Putin's elite circle believe Russia's war with Ukraine was a "catastrophic mistake that will set the country back for years", 10 sources told Bloomberg. FOLLOW BELOW FOR LIVE UPDATES...